<%# Terminal-style full-width statusline (R1, restyled for the terminal-identity
    redesign #1226). Default markup state is plain-CSS `hidden` (nothing to flash
    without JS, since this element has no meaning without it); keyboard_nav_controller
    #connect() reveals it -- unless the visitor is on a touch/no-precise-pointer device
    (R12), in which case it's never revealed at all.

    Hard constraint (keyboard-layer test contract, spec/support/keyboard_nav_helpers.rb
    + the keyboard_nav_* system specs): this element keeps id="keyboard-status-line",
    data-keyboard-nav-target="statusLine", starts with the "hidden" class, and contains
    data-keyboard-nav-target="statusLineText" whose text is exactly "-- NORMAL --". The
    inner flex row lives on a nested div (not this element) so the "hidden" toggle never
    has to fight a same-element "flex" utility for display-property precedence.

    aria-live="polite" so mode changes are announced without interrupting (deliberately
    never "assertive"). Path + hints come from StatuslineHelper, keyed on the current
    controller/action (design doc's Statusline section); an unmapped page renders "~/"
    with no hint group rather than raising. %>
<div
  id="keyboard-status-line"
  data-keyboard-nav-target="statusLine"
  class="hidden w-full border-t border-base-300 bg-base-200 font-mono text-[13px]"
>
  <div class="flex items-stretch">
    <span data-keyboard-nav-target="statusLineText" aria-live="polite" class="bg-primary text-primary-content font-bold px-4 py-1.5">-- NORMAL --</span>
    <span class="px-4 py-1.5 text-base-content/70"><%= statusline_path %></span>
    <% if statusline_hints.any? %>
      <span class="hidden md:flex ml-auto items-center gap-5 px-4 py-1.5 text-base-content/50">
        <% statusline_hints.each do |key, label| %>
          <span><span class="text-primary font-bold"><%= key %></span> <%= label %></span>
        <% end %>
      </span>
    <% end %>
  </div>
</div>
